Now we need a system to appoximate the shape of these weathers in 2D space using a starting X and Y coordinate and an ending Z and W coordinate. We should be writing this per cloud type per weather patter to a UBO with arrays for both weather coordinates, distance from players position/center of world and all cloud settings defined and the weathers settings that are appropriate too. So now there should be a valid UBO for shaders to read which will define all weather. The weathers may sometimes need multiple sqaures to get the area roughly approximated.\par
The weather should be sampled and readily available quite far away. I do not care if there is some overlap but there should not be a single inch of any area where we are not writing weather to the cpu side systems and the UBO.\par
Now visually there needs to be 2 seperate systems. A skybox and an overhead system. Both systems can draw from the same UBO.\par
The skybox should be rather straight forward. It will sample clouds in a range defined in EngineSettings both a near and far ring. These should be rather far from player/center of world. Now since we are sampling clouds in the sky far away they should natually appear on the horizon. We have the distance to determine this easily. We also have a vec 4 which should be in world space we are using to tell the sky where on the horizon to draw the clouds as well as cloud height and elevation and any other variables defined to draw the correct type of clouds at the correct types of clouds ont eh sky and distance can tell it how small or large to make them as well.\par
Now the overhead system is going to be more complex. We need to instance large stretched  mesh in accordance with the approximated weathers. One per cloud type per weather pattern. We can attach the instances cloud material from earlier to these boxes to tell them to render clouds inside of them based on the cloud settings defined. This gives enough variables to draw the correct types of clouds in every portion of the sky above the player with the correct types of clouds. To avoid clipping distances we need to keep the weather patters over the player so they should be settings.maxRenderDistance far away. Doing this alone however will cause a visual gap in displayed weathers so we will need to simulate distances. As we approach the settings.maxRenderDistance we get the weather which is being sampled in the near range fo the skybox. As we get closer to the player we get closer and closer to the actual weather being sampled in that spot int he world coordinates. Doing this will give us clouds which will blend with the sky, move over the terrain and avoid clipping distance issues with the cameras far render range. \par
